1.6 Background & State of the art

SpaceX decided to recover the Falcon 9 booster with propulsive landing after a few failures with traditional technology. There were many reasons to not use parachutes. First of all, it canβÄôt be controlled precisely. Secondly, this system does not stop the vehicle, it only slows the rocket down to a marginal speed. Then, this implies damaging the rocket at ground touchdown. To avoid that, the sea is normally used as a soft surface to absorb the impact. The problem is that saltwater can easily damage a lot of systems, which translates into more time and cost between launches. Nowadays, RocketLab is trying to recover the ο§¹rst stage of the Electron rocket using parachutes. It is currently splashing into the water, but the ο§¹nal goal is to catch the booster with an helicopter through the parachute. This is to avoid problems with extraction operation and saltwater.[1]

1.6.1 Parachute System
In the model rockets frame, the parachute system is the only method to recover the vehicle.
Advantages: It is less complex, less expensive and does not require advanced engineering knowledge to be used.
Disadvantages: It is not ο§²awless. The parachute might not be ejected and if it does, the strings might still get entangled. In case it opens late the rocket will hit the ground hard. Moreover, depending on the apogee the rocket can have a wide circle of recovery. Thus the exact position of touchdown canβÄôt be accurately estimated until it is launched.

1.6.2 Propulsive landing & BPS.SPACE
Barnard Propulsion Systems (BPS.SPACE)[2] is a small company that has been focused on model rocket propulsive landing. Their rockets have thrust vector control as in this project. They are developing a prototype capable of launching and landing. This project only covers the landing part due to time and resources limitations.
Advantages: It can be more reliable than a parachute. The vehicle does not hit the ground when it lands. Thus, avoiding deterioration of the rocket body-frame. It only requires to replace the engine/s to launch again.
Disadvantages: It is more complex than deploying a parachute. It is more expensive to implement. It requires advanced engineering skills to be developed and operated.

