8.1.1 PID
The PID function is the one in charge of calculating the required angles of the servos to control the attitude of the rocket. Its implementation is similar to the ODE45 simulation.
The problem with the integral term is that grows a lot, by integrating small errors. This can happen when the PID function is running while the rocket is ascending with the auxiliary vehicle, the phase where the T V C is not used. The rocket will start with erratic numbers if the rocket triggers the ignition and the integral term is not restored.The best way to avoid the issue is to restart the integral term periodically (based on an external condition). For this particular case, the integral error starts counting when the drop condition is met. Another option would be to restart the integral error using a condition based on gravity detection or apogee. The second problem to address is the limitations of the hardware. It has to take into account the operational limits of the actuators. The servos have a hardware limitation of ¬±180 degrees. However, they must use only ¬±6 degrees for control. By just adding and if/else condition this problem gets regulated. If the limit is exceeded the maximum is applied and the same goes for the minimum.

